2026-04-21 01:28:26 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Control module 3 output switch path / series conductor (12V line)', 'Control module 3 red LED / indicator branch (open circuit possibility)'] hypothesis_explanation='Measurements show that up to the input of control module 3, the 12 V and 0 V rails are correct and present. Inside control module 3, the input rails are still correct, but BOTH output conductors are at 0 V, and from module 4 onward everything remains at 0 V. There is no polarity inversion anywhere.\n\nIn this architecture, each control module should pass the 12 V rail straight through when its switch is ON. If the switch or its associated series path in module 3 is open or otherwise faulty, the 12 V rail would be interrupted at that module. The downstream cabling and modules then float and are pulled or clamped to 0 V via internal indicator circuits, resulting in both output conductors of module 3 (and every subsequent module input) reading 0 V as observed.\n\nTherefore the most probable root cause is an internal open‑circuit fault in control module 3—either in the switch contacts or the series conductor for the 12 V line, or less likely an internal fault related to the indicator branch causing the line not to be passed through. Replacing or repairing control module 3 should restore 12 V continuity to the rest of the chain and allow the downstream LEDs and the load lamp to operate.'
