2026-04-21 01:29:14 | DEBUG    | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | INPUT [tail only with new content. Full content is concatenation of all previous log entries]: 
Someone executed a (additional) diagnostic action on the system. The action (type, target_component, description, outcome) was: 
TYPE: Test,
TARGET: Control module 3 internal wiring vs external cable pairing,
DESCRIPTION: With battery inserted and all switches ON, completely disconnect control module 3 from modules 2 and 4. Using an ohmmeter (power OFF for resistance checks), first identify on module 3 which two terminals belong to the same through‑pair (series path) by checking continuity between its four cable pins and the internal switch/indicator circuit. Then, with power OFF, check each loose cable pair between modules 2–3 and 3–4 to determine which conductors are actually continuous to each other (trace 12 V line and 0 V line separately). Compare to the required series topology to see whether any of the four cables around module 3 are cross‑connected (mis‑paired) rather than passed straight through. This will reveal a wiring/configuration error rather than an internal component failure.,
RESULT: Continuity tests show that for module 3 the negative path is continuous straight through (Control Input Cable (−) 3 → Control Output Cable (−) 3 ≈ 0.1 Ω), while the positive path is not (Control Input Cable (+) 3 → Control Output Cable (+) 3 is open). POLARITY INVERSION DETECTED: Control Input Cable (+) 3 is instead continuous to Control Output Cable (−) 3 (≈ 2.12 Ω), indicating these two conductors form a through‑pair inside module 3. All external inter‑module cabling (module 2 → 3 and 3 → 4) is straight‑through with matching polarities (e.g., 2(+) → 3(+), 2(−) → 3(−), 3(+) → 4(+), 3(−) → 4(−)).
Current persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:
No circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.


2026-04-21 01:29:14 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Control module 3 internal positive-path switching network / through-pair topology (miswired pairing of Input (+) 3 with Output (−) 3 and isolation of Output (+) 3 from the 12 V series path)'] hypothesis_explanation='Tests show that the external cables between modules 2–3 and 3–4 are correctly wired with matching polarities, and that within control module 3 the nominal negative through-path is continuous straight through. However, the nominal positive path is open between Input (+) 3 and Output (+) 3, while Input (+) 3 is instead continuous to Output (−) 3, i.e., these two conductors form the internal through-pair. That means module 3 is internally misconfigured: its internal wiring/switch network pairs the wrong two terminals together. In operation this prevents 12 V from propagating correctly beyond module 3 even though the module may have intact components. The root cause is therefore a configuration/wiring error inside control module 3: the positive-path through-pair is miswired, with Input (+) 3 incorrectly bonded to Output (−) 3 and Output (+) 3 left disconnected from the series chain. Repair consists of rewiring/restoring the correct internal pairing so that Input (+) 3 is continuous to Output (+) 3 and the switch/indicator branch is connected between the proper + and 0 V lines.'
